## Advanced Routing and Controller Design Patterns

In Module 1, you learned the basics of setting up RESTful routes in Express. Now it's time to elevate your API design by mastering **dynamic routing techniques** and **controller layer optimizations**. Whether you're building a simple blog or a complex e-commerce platform, these advanced patterns will help you create clean, scalable, and maintainable APIs.

---

## Dynamic Routing Techniques

### Parameterized Routes

Express allows you to define routes with **dynamic parameters** using the colon (`:`) syntax. These parameters are automatically extracted and passed to your route handlers as part of the `req.params` object.

**Example: Fetching a User by ID**

```javascript
// In your route file (e.g., routes/users.js)
const express = require('express');
const router = express.Router();

// GET /users/:id
router.get('/:id', (req, res) => {
  const userId = req.params.id;
  // Fetch user from database
  res.json({ id: userId, name: "Jane Doe" });
});
```

This pattern is perfect for endpoints like `/users/:id`, `/products/:id`, or `/orders/:orderId`.

> 💡 **Pro Tip**: Always validate route parameters (e.g., using `express-validator`) to prevent injection or invalid IDs.

---

### Nested Routes

For APIs with hierarchical resources (e.g., `users/{id}/posts`), **nested routing** keeps your code organized and mirrors the resource structure.

**Example: User Posts Endpoint**

```javascript
// routes/users.js
router.get('/:userId/posts', (req, res) => {
  const userId = req.params.userId;
  // Fetch posts by userId
  res.json([{ id: 1, title: "First Post" }]);
});

// routes/posts.js
router.get('/:postId', (req, res) => {
  const postId = req.params.postId;
  // Fetch post by postId
  res.json({ id: postId, title: "First Post", content: "..." });
});
```

While Express supports nested routes, for complex APIs, it's better to **flatten the structure** and manage relationships at the controller level. This avoids deeply nested route files and improves maintainability.

---

### Wildcard and Regex Routes

Express also supports **wildcard routes** (`*`) and **regular expressions** for advanced routing.

```javascript
// Matches any route starting with /docs
router.get('/docs/*', (req, res) => {
  res.send("Documentation endpoint");
});

// Matches only numeric IDs
router.get(/^\/\d+$/, (req, res) => {
  res.send("Numeric route matched");
});
```

> ⚠️ Use wildcards and regex sparingly—they can make routing logic harder to debug.

---

## Controller Layer Optimizations

Controllers are the heart of your API—they handle business logic and respond to requests. Let’s explore **reusable controller factories** and **dependency injection** to make your controllers more maintainable.

---

### Controller Factories for Reusability

Instead of writing repetitive controller functions, **create reusable factory functions** that generate controllers with shared logic.

**Example: Generic CRUD Controller Factory**

```javascript
// utils/crudController.js
const createCrudController = (model) => ({
  getAll: async (req, res) => {
    const items = await model.find();
    res.json(items);
  },
  getOne: async (req, res) => {
    const item = await model.findById(req.params.id);
    if (!item) return res.status(404).json({ error: "Not found" });
    res.json(item);
  },
  create: async (req, res) => {
    const newItem = await model.create(req.body);
    res.status(201).json(newItem);
  },
  update: async (req, res) => {
    const updatedItem = await model.findByIdAndUpdate(
      req.params.id,
      req.body,
      { new: true }
    );
    if (!updatedItem) return res.status(404).json({ error: "Not found" });
    res.json(updatedItem);
  },
  delete: async (req, res) => {
    const deletedItem = await model.findByIdAndDelete(req.params.id);
    if (!deletedItem) return res.status(404).json({ error: "Not found" });
    res.status(204).end();
  },
});

module.exports = createCrudController;
```

Now you can generate controllers for any model:

```javascript
// controllers/userController.js
const User = require('../models/User');
const createCrudController = require('../utils/crudController');

module.exports = createCrudController(User);
```

Then attach them to routes:

```javascript
// routes/users.js
const express = require('express');
const router = express.Router();
const userController = require('../controllers/userController');

router.get('/', userController.getAll);
router.post('/', userController.create);
router.get('/:id', userController.getOne);
router.put('/:id', userController.update);
router.delete('/:id', userController.delete);

module.exports = router;
```

This pattern **dramatically reduces boilerplate** and ensures consistent behavior across all your CRUD endpoints.

---

### Dependency Injection in Controllers

Instead of tightly coupling controllers to services or models, **inject dependencies** to make them more testable and flexible.

**Example: Injecting a User Service**

```javascript
// services/UserService.js
class UserService {
  constructor(userModel) {
    this.userModel = userModel;
  }

  async getUser(id) {
    return this.userModel.findById(id);
  }
}

module.exports = UserService;
```

Now, inject it into your controller:

```javascript
// controllers/userController.js
module.exports = {
  getUser: async (req, res) => {
    const user = await req.userService.getUser(req.params.id);
    if (!user) return res.status(404).json({ error: "User not found" });
    res.json(user);
  },
};
```

But how do we inject `userService` into the controller? Use **express routers with middleware** or instantiate the controller with dependencies.

**Option 1: Using Express Router with app-level middleware**

```javascript
// app.js
const UserService = require('./services/UserService');
const UserModel = require('./models/User');
const userService = new UserService(UserModel);

// Attach to req
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  req.userService = userService;
  next();
});

// Now req.userService is available in all routes
```

**Option 2: Factory Function with Dependency Injection**

```javascript
// controllers/userController.js
const createUserController = (userService) => ({
  getUser: async (req, res) => {
    const user = await userService.getUser(req.params.id);
    if (!user) return res.status(404).json({ error: "User not found" });
    res.json(user);
  },
});

// In route setup:
const userService = new UserService(UserModel);
const userController = createUserController(userService);
```

This approach makes your controllers **pure functions**, easier to test, and decoupled from external dependencies.

---

## Route Versioning and Middleware Control

### Route Versioning

As your API evolves, you need a way to **introduce changes without breaking existing clients**. Route versioning is a standard practice.

**Example: API Versioning with Prefix**

```javascript
// v1 routes
const express = require('express');
const routerV1 = express.Router();

routerV1.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ version: "v1" }); // Old user format
});

// v2 routes
const routerV2 = express.Router();

routerV2.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ version: "v2", users: [] }); // New user format
});

// Mount versions
app.use('/api/v1', routerV1);
app.use('/api/v2', routerV2);
```

Alternatively, use **header-based versioning** or **URL parameters**:

```javascript
// Header-based versioning
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  const version = req.headers['x-api-version'] || 'v1';
  if (version === 'v1') {
    require('./routes/v1')(app);
  } else if (version === 'v2') {
    require('./routes/v2')(app);
  } else {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "Unsupported version" });
  }
});
```

> ✅ Best Practice: Use **prefix-based versioning** for simplicity and clarity.

---

### Conditional Middleware Execution

Not all middleware should run on every route. Use **conditional logic** to apply middleware only when needed.

**Example: Conditional Authentication**

```javascript
// Check if user is admin
const isAdmin = (req, res, next) => {
  if (req.user && req.user.role === 'admin') {
    next();
  } else {
    res.status(403).json({ error: "Access denied" });
  }
};

// Only apply to admin routes
router.get('/admin/dashboard', isAdmin, adminController.getDashboard);
```

**Example: Rate Limiting by Endpoint**

```javascript
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

// Apply only to login endpoint
router.post('/login', rateLimit({ windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, max: 5 }), authController.login);
```

This increases performance

## Chapter 3: Database Integration and ORM/ODM Mastery

Building a REST API is only half the battle. The real magic happens when your API seamlessly interacts with a persistent data store—whether it's a relational database like PostgreSQL or a NoSQL store like MongoDB. In this chapter, we dive deep into **advanced data persistence** using ORMs (Object-Relational Mappers) and ODMs (Object-Document Mappers), with a focus on performance, scalability, and maintainability.

By the end of this chapter, you'll be able to:
- Integrate Sequelize or TypeORM for complex relational queries
- Optimize MongoDB operations using Mongoose aggregation pipelines
- Design schema migrations and manage database transactions efficiently

---

## 1. Choosing the Right ORM/ODM

When working with Node.js and Express, two popular tools emerge for data persistence:

- **Sequelize** – A promise-based ORM for SQL databases (PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite, etc.)
- **TypeORM** – A TypeScript-first ORM with support for both Active Record and Data Mapper patterns
- **Mongoose** – A leading ODM for MongoDB, offering schema validation and rich query building

> **Best Practice**: Use an ORM/ODM to abstract raw SQL/NoSQL syntax, reduce boilerplate, and enforce data integrity.

---

## 2. Integrating Sequelize for SQL Databases

Sequelize is ideal when your application requires **structured data with relationships**—like users, orders, and products in an e-commerce system.

### Installation & Setup

```bash
npm install sequelize pg pg-hstore
```

### Database Connection

```javascript
const { Sequelize } = require('sequelize');

// Initialize connection to PostgreSQL
const sequelize = new Sequelize('database_name', 'username', 'password', {
  host: 'localhost',
  dialect: 'postgres',
  logging: false, // Disable logging in production
  pool: {
    max: 5,
    min: 0,
    acquire: 30000,
    idle: 10000
  }
});

// Test connection
sequelize.authenticate()
  .then(() => console.log('Database connected!'))
  .catch(err => console.error('Connection error:', err));
```

### Defining Models and Relationships

Let’s model a `User` and `Order` relationship.

```javascript
const User = sequelize.define('User', {
  id: {
    type: Sequelize.INTEGER,
    primaryKey: true,
    autoIncrement: true
  },
  name: {
    type: Sequelize.STRING,
    allowNull: false
  },
  email: {
    type: Sequelize.STRING,
    unique: true,
    validate: { isEmail: true }
  }
});

const Order = sequelize.define('Order', {
  id: { type: Sequelize.INTEGER, primaryKey: true, autoIncrement: true },
  product: { type: Sequelize.STRING, allowNull: false },
  amount: { type: Sequelize.DECIMAL(10, 2), allowNull: false }
});

// Define One-to-Many relationship
User.hasMany(Order, { foreignKey: 'userId', onDelete: 'CASCADE' });
Order.belongsTo(User, { foreignKey: 'userId' });
```

> 💡 **Performance Tip**: Use `include` to eager-load associated models and avoid the N+1 query problem.

### Complex Query Example: Fetching Users with Their Orders

```javascript
const usersWithOrders = await User.findAll({
  include: [{
    model: Order,
    attributes: ['product', 'amount']
  }],
  where: { email: { [Sequelize.Op.like]: '%@example.com' } },
  order: [['name', 'ASC']]
});
```

This generates a single optimized SQL query with a `JOIN`, improving performance significantly.

---

## 3. Advanced Querying with TypeORM

TypeORM supports both **Active Record** and **Repository** patterns, making it ideal for TypeScript projects.

### Installation

```bash
npm install typeorm reflect-metadata pg
```

> 🔑 **Important**: Enable `emitDecoratorMetadata` and `experimentalDecorators` in `tsconfig.json`.

### Entity Definition

```typescript
import { Entity, PrimaryGeneratedColumn, Column, OneToMany } from 'typeorm';
import { Order } from './order.entity';

@Entity()
export class User {
  @PrimaryGeneratedColumn()
  id: number;

  @Column()
  name: string;

  @Column({ unique: true })
  email: string;

  @OneToMany(() => Order, order => order.user)
  orders: Order[];
}
```

### Fetching with Relations (Eager Loading)

```typescript
const userRepository = getRepository(User);
const usersWithOrders = await userRepository.find({
  relations: ['orders'],
  where: { email: Like('%@example.com') },
  order: { name: 'ASC' }
});
```

> ✅ **Best Practice**: TypeORM supports complex joins and can optimize queries using `QueryBuilder`.

### Using QueryBuilder for Complex Conditions

```typescript
const users = await getRepository(User)
  .createQueryBuilder('user')
  .leftJoinAndSelect('user.orders', 'order')
  .where('user.email LIKE :email', { email: '%@example.com' })
  .andWhere('order.amount > :minAmount', { minAmount: 100 })
  .orderBy('user.name', 'ASC')
  .getMany();
```

This is more powerful than `find()` and supports advanced filtering, grouping, and subqueries.

---

## 4. Schema Migrations with Sequelize and TypeORM

Migrations allow you to version your database schema and apply changes safely.

### Sequelize Migrations

Create a migration:

```bash
npx sequelize-cli migration:generate --name add-role-to-user
```

Define up/down:

```javascript
module.exports = {
  up: async (queryInterface, Sequelize) => {
    await queryInterface.addColumn('Users', 'role', {
      type: Sequelize.STRING,
      defaultValue: 'user'
    });
  },
  down: async (queryInterface) => {
    await queryInterface.removeColumn('Users', 'role');
  }
};
```

Run migrations:

```bash
npx sequelize-cli db:migrate
```

> 🔐 **Best Practice**: Always back up your database before running migrations in production.

### TypeORM Migrations

Generate migration:

```bash
npx typeorm migration:create -n AddRoleToUser
```

Define migration:

```typescript
import { MigrationInterface, QueryRunner } from 'typeorm';

export class AddRoleToUser1717500000000 implements MigrationInterface {
  public async up(queryRunner: QueryRunner): Promise<void> {
    await queryRunner.query(`ALTER TABLE "user" ADD COLUMN "role" varchar(255) DEFAULT 'user'`);
  }

  public async down(queryRunner: QueryRunner): Promise<void> {
    await queryRunner.query(`ALTER TABLE "user" DROP COLUMN "role"`);
  }
}
```

Apply migrations:

```bash
npx typeorm migration:run
```

> 📌 **Tip**: Use `--dry-run` to test migrations before applying.

---

## 5. Optimizing MongoDB with Mongoose Aggregation Pipelines

When working with NoSQL, **Mongoose** provides powerful tools for querying and transforming data using the **aggregation framework**.

### Installation

```bash
npm install mongoose
```

### Define Schema and Model

```javascript
const mongoose = require('mongoose');

const orderSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  userId: { type: mongoose.Schema.Types.ObjectId, ref: 'User' },
  product: String,
  amount: Number,
  status: { type: String, enum: ['pending', 'completed', 'cancelled'] },
  createdAt: { type: Date, default: Date.now }
});

const Order = mongoose.model('Order', orderSchema);
```

### Aggregation Example: Monthly Sales Summary

```javascript
const result = await Order.aggregate([
  { $match: { status: 'completed' } }, // Filter completed orders
  { $group: {
      _id: { month: { $month: "$createdAt" }, year: { $year: "$createdAt" } },
      totalSales: { $sum: "$amount" },
      count: { $sum: 1 }
  }},
  { $sort: { "_id.year": 1, "_id.month": 1 } }
]);

console.log(result);
```

**Output Example**:
```json
[
  { "_id": { "month": 3, "year": 2024 }, "totalSales": 1500.75, "count": 20 },
  { "_id": { "month": 4, "year": 2024 }, "totalSales": 2200.00, "count": 28 }
]
```

This pipeline:
1. Filters completed orders
2. Groups by month/year
3. Calculates total sales and count
4. Sorts chronologically

> 🚀 **Performance Insight**: Aggregation pipelines run on the database server, reducing data transfer and improving speed.

---

