# Chapter 2: Module 2: Advanced Routing and Controller Design Patterns

## Advanced Routing and Controller Design Patterns

In Module 1, you learned the basics of setting up RESTful routes in Express. Now it's time to elevate your API design by mastering **dynamic routing techniques** and **controller layer optimizations**. Whether you're building a simple blog or a complex e-commerce platform, these advanced patterns will help you create clean, scalable, and maintainable APIs.

---

## Dynamic Routing Techniques

### Parameterized Routes

Express allows you to define routes with **dynamic parameters** using the colon (`:`) syntax. These parameters are automatically extracted and passed to your route handlers as part of the `req.params` object.

**Example: Fetching a User by ID**

```javascript
// In your route file (e.g., routes/users.js)
const express = require('express');
const router = express.Router();

// GET /users/:id
router.get('/:id', (req, res) => {
  const userId = req.params.id;
  // Fetch user from database
  res.json({ id: userId, name: "Jane Doe" });
});
```

This pattern is perfect for endpoints like `/users/:id`, `/products/:id`, or `/orders/:orderId`.

> 💡 **Pro Tip**: Always validate route parameters (e.g., using `express-validator`) to prevent injection or invalid IDs.

---

### Nested Routes

For APIs with hierarchical resources (e.g., `users/{id}/posts`), **nested routing** keeps your code organized and mirrors the resource structure.

**Example: User Posts Endpoint**

```javascript
// routes/users.js
router.get('/:userId/posts', (req, res) => {
  const userId = req.params.userId;
  // Fetch posts by userId
  res.json([{ id: 1, title: "First Post" }]);
});

// routes/posts.js
router.get('/:postId', (req, res) => {
  const postId = req.params.postId;
  // Fetch post by postId
  res.json({ id: postId, title: "First Post", content: "..." });
});
```

While Express supports nested routes, for complex APIs, it's better to **flatten the structure** and manage relationships at the controller level. This avoids deeply nested route files and improves maintainability.

---

### Wildcard and Regex Routes

Express also supports **wildcard routes** (`*`) and **regular expressions** for advanced routing.

```javascript
// Matches any route starting with /docs
router.get('/docs/*', (req, res) => {
  res.send("Documentation endpoint");
});

// Matches only numeric IDs
router.get(/^\/\d+$/, (req, res) => {
  res.send("Numeric route matched");
});
```

> ⚠️ Use wildcards and regex sparingly—they can make routing logic harder to debug.

---

## Controller Layer Optimizations

Controllers are the heart of your API—they handle business logic and respond to requests. Let’s explore **reusable controller factories** and **dependency injection** to make your controllers more maintainable.

---

### Controller Factories for Reusability

Instead of writing repetitive controller functions, **create reusable factory functions** that generate controllers with shared logic.

**Example: Generic CRUD Controller Factory**

```javascript
// utils/crudController.js
const createCrudController = (model) => ({
  getAll: async (req, res) => {
    const items = await model.find();
    res.json(items);
  },
  getOne: async (req, res) => {
    const item = await model.findById(req.params.id);
    if (!item) return res.status(404).json({ error: "Not found" });
    res.json(item);
  },
  create: async (req, res) => {
    const newItem = await model.create(req.body);
    res.status(201).json(newItem);
  },
  update: async (req, res) => {
    const updatedItem = await model.findByIdAndUpdate(
      req.params.id,
      req.body,
      { new: true }
    );
    if (!updatedItem) return res.status(404).json({ error: "Not found" });
    res.json(updatedItem);
  },
  delete: async (req, res) => {
    const deletedItem = await model.findByIdAndDelete(req.params.id);
    if (!deletedItem) return res.status(404).json({ error: "Not found" });
    res.status(204).end();
  },
});

module.exports = createCrudController;
```

Now you can generate controllers for any model:

```javascript
// controllers/userController.js
const User = require('../models/User');
const createCrudController = require('../utils/crudController');

module.exports = createCrudController(User);
```

Then attach them to routes:

```javascript
// routes/users.js
const express = require('express');
const router = express.Router();
const userController = require('../controllers/userController');

router.get('/', userController.getAll);
router.post('/', userController.create);
router.get('/:id', userController.getOne);
router.put('/:id', userController.update);
router.delete('/:id', userController.delete);

module.exports = router;
```

This pattern **dramatically reduces boilerplate** and ensures consistent behavior across all your CRUD endpoints.

---

### Dependency Injection in Controllers

Instead of tightly coupling controllers to services or models, **inject dependencies** to make them more testable and flexible.

**Example: Injecting a User Service**

```javascript
// services/UserService.js
class UserService {
  constructor(userModel) {
    this.userModel = userModel;
  }

  async getUser(id) {
    return this.userModel.findById(id);
  }
}

module.exports = UserService;
```

Now, inject it into your controller:

```javascript
// controllers/userController.js
module.exports = {
  getUser: async (req, res) => {
    const user = await req.userService.getUser(req.params.id);
    if (!user) return res.status(404).json({ error: "User not found" });
    res.json(user);
  },
};
```

But how do we inject `userService` into the controller? Use **express routers with middleware** or instantiate the controller with dependencies.

**Option 1: Using Express Router with app-level middleware**

```javascript
// app.js
const UserService = require('./services/UserService');
const UserModel = require('./models/User');
const userService = new UserService(UserModel);

// Attach to req
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  req.userService = userService;
  next();
});

// Now req.userService is available in all routes
```

**Option 2: Factory Function with Dependency Injection**

```javascript
// controllers/userController.js
const createUserController = (userService) => ({
  getUser: async (req, res) => {
    const user = await userService.getUser(req.params.id);
    if (!user) return res.status(404).json({ error: "User not found" });
    res.json(user);
  },
});

// In route setup:
const userService = new UserService(UserModel);
const userController = createUserController(userService);
```

This approach makes your controllers **pure functions**, easier to test, and decoupled from external dependencies.

---

## Route Versioning and Middleware Control

### Route Versioning

As your API evolves, you need a way to **introduce changes without breaking existing clients**. Route versioning is a standard practice.

**Example: API Versioning with Prefix**

```javascript
// v1 routes
const express = require('express');
const routerV1 = express.Router();

routerV1.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ version: "v1" }); // Old user format
});

// v2 routes
const routerV2 = express.Router();

routerV2.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ version: "v2", users: [] }); // New user format
});

// Mount versions
app.use('/api/v1', routerV1);
app.use('/api/v2', routerV2);
```

Alternatively, use **header-based versioning** or **URL parameters**:

```javascript
// Header-based versioning
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  const version = req.headers['x-api-version'] || 'v1';
  if (version === 'v1') {
    require('./routes/v1')(app);
  } else if (version === 'v2') {
    require('./routes/v2')(app);
  } else {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "Unsupported version" });
  }
});
```

> ✅ Best Practice: Use **prefix-based versioning** for simplicity and clarity.

---

### Conditional Middleware Execution

Not all middleware should run on every route. Use **conditional logic** to apply middleware only when needed.

**Example: Conditional Authentication**

```javascript
// Check if user is admin
const isAdmin = (req, res, next) => {
  if (req.user && req.user.role === 'admin') {
    next();
  } else {
    res.status(403).json({ error: "Access denied" });
  }
};

// Only apply to admin routes
router.get('/admin/dashboard', isAdmin, adminController.getDashboard);
```

**Example: Rate Limiting by Endpoint**

```javascript
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

// Apply only to login endpoint
router.post('/login', rateLimit({ windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, max: 5 }), authController.login);
```

This increases performance

