## 5. API Versioning with OpenAPI and Swagger

Versioning is critical in production APIs. OpenAPI supports versioning in both the **URL** and the **specification**.

### Strategy: URL Path Versioning

```
https://api.example.com/v1/tasks
https://api.example.com/v2/tasks
```

### Step 5: Multiple OpenAPI Specs for Each Version

```js
// v1 spec
const specsV1 = swaggerJsdoc({
  definition: {
    openapi: '3.1.0',
    info: { title: 'Task Manager API', version: '1.0.0' },
    // ...
  },
  apis: ['./src/routes/v1/*.js'],
});

// v2 spec
const specsV2 = swaggerJsdoc({
  definition: {
    openapi: '3.1.0',
    info: { title: 'Task Manager API', version: '2.0.0' },
    // Updated paths, schemas
  },
  apis: ['./src/routes/v2/*.js'],
});
```

### Step 6: Serve Versioned Docs

```js
app.use('/api-docs/v1', swaggerUi.serve, swaggerUi.setup(specsV1));
app.use('/api-docs/v2', swaggerUi.serve, swaggerUi.setup(specsV2));
```

Now users can explore both versions independently.

> 🔄 Tip: Use **API gateways** or **reverse proxies** (e.g., Nginx) to route `/v1/*` and `/v2/*` to different Express apps if needed.

---

## 6. Build Custom Documentation Portals

While Swagger UI is powerful, you may want a **branded portal** with additional context, tutorials, or SDK examples.

### Option 1: Embed Swagger UI in a Custom Page

```html
<!-- /docs/index.html -->
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>My API Docs</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://unpkg.com/swagger-ui-dist@5/swagger-ui.css">
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Task Manager API</h1>
  <div id="swagger-ui"></div>
  <script src="https://unpkg.com/swagger-ui-dist@5/swagger-ui-bundle.js"></script>
  <script>
    const ui = SwaggerUIBundle({
      url: '/api-docs/v1',
      dom_id: '#swagger-ui',
      presets: [SwaggerUIBundle.presets.apis],
      layout: "BaseLayout",
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

Serve this via Express:

```js
app.use('/docs', express.static('public/docs'));
```

